import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import folium
from folium.plugins import HeatMap, MarkerCluster, TimestampedGeoJson
import json
import plotly.express as px
import plotly.graph_objects as go
In[10]:
# Load the datasets to inspect their structure
deaths_df = pd.read_csv('deaths.csv')
pumps_df = pd.read_csv('pumps.csv')
snow_dates_df = pd.read_csv('snow_dates.csv')
In[11]:
# Define the center of the map based on the average location of the deaths and pumps
center_lat = deaths_df['x_latitude'].mean()
center_lon = deaths_df['y_longitude'].mean()

# Create a folium map centered around the area with pump and death data
cholera_map = folium.Map(location=[center_lat, center_lon], zoom_start=16)
In[13]:
# Add pumps with blue markers
for _, row in pumps_df.iterrows():
    folium.Marker(
        location=[row['x_coordinate'], row['y_coordinate']],
        popup=f"Pump: {row['pump_name']}",
        icon=folium.Icon(color='blue', icon='tint')
    ).add_to(cholera_map)
In[17]:
# Using a Marker doesnt reflect the amount of data, so I made the iteration 1: using a CircleMarker so that the size of the marker can vary with the number of deaths.
# Add deaths with graduated circle markers based on the death count
marker_cluster = MarkerCluster().add_to(cholera_map)
for _, row in deaths_df.iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[row['x_latitude'], row['y_longitude']],
        radius=row['death_count'] * 2,  # Scale marker size by death count
        color='crimson',
        fill=True,
        fill_color='crimson',
        fill_opacity=0.6,
        popup=f"Deaths: {row['death_count']}"
    ).add_to(marker_cluster)
In[19]:
# Because it is difficult to interpret areas with multiple markers, that I deside to do iteration 2 - Adding Heatmap.
# Add a heatmap layer to highlight areas with higher death densities
heat_data = deaths_df[['x_latitude', 'y_longitude']].values.tolist()
HeatMap(heat_data, radius=12, blur=15).add_to(cholera_map)
